@Cyrus is right when he says that [[X]HTML cannot be parsed with a regex](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1732348/regex-match-open-tags-except-xhtml-self-contained-tags/1732454#1732454).


But if you are sure the input will always look like this, and since the input isn&#39;t as complex, you can, in fact, do it with sed:

    sed -E &#39;s|&lt;StartDateTime&gt;([0-9]{4}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{2})T([0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}[A-Z])&lt;/StartDateTime&gt;|&lt;date&gt;\1&lt;/date&gt;\n    &lt;time&gt;\2&lt;/time&gt;|g&#39;

This expression uses capturing groups which you can later [reference](https://www.gnu.org/software/sed/manual/html_node/Back_002dreferences-and-Subexpressions.html) in the substitution with `&#39;\&#39; ` followed by the index of the group, `\1` and `\2` in this case.

